{"text": "






Chapter Ten

Wave Optics


10.1  Introduction
In 1637 Descartes gave the corpuscular model of light and derived Snell’s law.", "fibs": ["Chapter"]}
{"text": "It explained the laws of reflection and refraction of light at an interface.", "fibs": ["reflection"]}
{"text": "The corpuscular model predicted that if the ray of light (on refraction) bends towards the normal then the speed of light would be greater in the second medium.", "fibs": ["model"]}
{"text": "This corpuscular model of light was further developed by Isaac Newton in his famous book entitled OPTICKS and because of the tremendous popularity of this book, the corpuscular model is very often attributed to Newton.", "fibs": ["model"]}
{"text": "In 1678, the Dutch physicist Christiaan Huygens put forward the wave theory of light – it is this wave model of light that we will discuss in this chapter.", "fibs": ["physicist"]}
{"text": "As we will see, the wave model could satisfactorily explain the phenomena of reflection and refraction; however, it predicted that on refraction if the wave bends towards the normal then the speed of light would be less in the second medium.", "fibs": ["wave"]}
{"text": "This is in contradiction to the prediction made by using the corpuscular model of light.", "fibs": ["contradiction"]}
{"text": "It was much later confirmed by experiments where it was shown that the speed of light in water is less than the speed in air confirming the prediction of the wave model; Foucault carried out this experiment in 1850.", "fibs": ["speed"]}
{"text": "The wave theory was not readily accepted primarily because of Newton’s authority and also because light could travel through vacuum and it was felt that a wave would always require a medium to propagate from one point to the other.", "fibs": ["wave"]}
{"text": "However, when Thomas Young performed his famous interference experiment in 1801, it was firmly established that light is indeed a wave phenomenon.", "fibs": ["interference"]}
{"text": "The wavelength of visible light was measured and found to be extremely small; for example, the wavelength of yellow light is about 0.6 µm.", "fibs": ["wavelength"]}
{"text": "Because of the smallness of the wavelength of visible light (in comparison to the dimensions of typical mirrors and lenses), light can be assumed to approximately travel in straight lines.", "fibs": ["smallness"]}
{"text": "This is the field of geometrical optics, which we had discussed in the previous chapter.", "fibs": ["field"]}
{"text": "Indeed, the branch of optics in which one completely neglects the finiteness of the wavelength is called geometrical optics and a ray is defined as the path of energy propagation in the limit of wavelength tending to zero.", "fibs": ["branch"]}
{"text": "After the interference experiment of Young in 1801, for the next 40 years or so, many experiments were carried out involving the interference and diffraction of lightwaves; these experiments could only be satisfactorily explained by assuming a wave model of light.", "fibs": ["interference"]}
{"text": "Thus, around the middle of the nineteenth century, the wave theory seemed to be very well established.", "fibs": ["middle"]}
{"text": "The only major difficulty was that since it was thought that a wave required a medium for its propagation, how could light waves propagate through vacuum.", "fibs": ["difficulty"]}
{"text": "This was explained when Maxwell put forward his famous electromagnetic theory of light.", "fibs": ["theory"]}
{"text": "Maxwell had developed a set of equations describing the laws of electricity and magnetism and using these equations he derived what is known as the wave equation from which he predicted the existence of electromagnetic waves*.", "fibs": ["electricity"]}
{"text": "From the wave equation, Maxwell could calculate the speed of electromagnetic waves in free space and he found that the theoretical value was very close to the measured value of speed of light.", "fibs": ["wave"]}
{"text": "From this, he propounded that light must be an electromagnetic wave.", "fibs": ["light"]}
{"text": "Thus, according to Maxwell, light waves are associated with changing electric and magnetic fields; changing electric field produces a time and space varying magnetic field and a changing magnetic field produces a time and space varying electric field.", "fibs": ["light"]}
{"text": "The changing electric and magnetic fields result in the propagation of electromagnetic waves (or light waves) even in vacuum.", "fibs": ["result"]}
{"text": "In this chapter we will first discuss the original formulation of the Huygens principle and derive the laws of reflection and refraction.", "fibs": ["chapter"]}
{"text": "In Sections 10.4 and 10.5, we will discuss the phenomenon of interference which is based on the principle of superposition.", "fibs": ["phenomenon"]}
{"text": "In Section 10.6 we will discuss the phenomenon of diffraction which is based on Huygens-Fresnel principle.", "fibs": ["Section"]}
{"text": "Finally in Section 10.7 we will discuss the phenomenon of polarisation which is based on the fact that the light waves are transverse electromagnetic waves.", "fibs": ["Section"]}
{"text": "*	Maxwell had predicted the existence of electromagnetic waves around 1855; it was much later (around 1890) that Heinrich Hertz produced radiowaves in the laboratory.", "fibs": ["existence"]}
{"text": "J.C. Bose and G. Marconi made practical applications of the Hertzian waves




Does light travel in a straight line?", "fibs": ["light"]}
{"text": "Light travels in a straight line in Class VI; it does not do so in Class XII and beyond!", "fibs": ["line"]}
{"text": "Surprised, aren’t you?", "fibs": ["aren"]}
{"text": "In school, you are shown an experiment in which you take three cardboards with pinholes in them, place a candle on one side and look from the other side.", "fibs": ["school"]}
{"text": "If the flame of the candle and the three pinholes are in a straight line, you can see the candle.", "fibs": ["flame"]}
{"text": "Even if one of them is displaced a little, you cannot see the candle.", "fibs": ["candle"]}
{"text": "This proves, so your teacher says, that light travels in a straight line.", "fibs": ["teacher"]}
{"text": "In the present book, there are two consecutive chapters, one on ray optics and the other on wave optics.", "fibs": ["book"]}
{"text": "Ray optics is based on rectilinear propagation of light, and deals with mirrors, lenses, reflection, refraction, etc.", "fibs": ["propagation"]}
{"text": "Then you come to the chapter on wave optics, and you are told that light travels as a wave, that it can bend around objects, it can diffract and interfere, etc.", "fibs": ["chapter"]}
{"text": "In optical region, light has a wavelength of about half a micrometre.", "fibs": ["region"]}
{"text": "If it encounters an obstacle of about this size, it can bend around it and can be seen on the other side.", "fibs": ["obstacle"]}
{"text": "Thus a micrometre size obstacle will not be able to stop a light ray.", "fibs": ["micrometre"]}
{"text": "If the obstacle is much larger, however, light will not be able to bend to that extent, and will not be seen on the other side.", "fibs": ["obstacle"]}
{"text": "This is a property of a wave in general, and can be seen in sound waves too.", "fibs": ["property"]}
{"text": "The sound wave of our speech has a wavelength of about 50cm to 1 m. If it meets an obstacle of the size of a few metres, it bends around it and reaches points behind the obstacle.", "fibs": ["sound"]}
{"text": "But when it comes across a larger obstacle of a few hundred metres, such as a hillock, most of it is reflected and is heard as an echo.", "fibs": ["obstacle"]}
{"text": "Then what about the primary school experiment?", "fibs": ["school"]}
{"text": "What happens there is that when we move any cardboard, the displacement is of the order of a few millimetres, which is much larger than the wavelength of light.", "fibs": ["move"]}
{"text": "Hence the candle cannot be seen.", "fibs": ["candle"]}
{"text": "If we are able to move one of the cardboards by a micrometer or less, light will be able to diffract, and the candle will still be seen.", "fibs": ["move"]}
{"text": "One could add to the first sentence in this box: It learns how to bend as it grows up!", "fibs": ["sentence"]}
{"text": "10.2  Huygens Principle
We would first define a wavefront: when we drop a small stone on a calm pool of water, waves spread out from the point of impact.", "fibs": ["Principle"]}
{"text": "Every point on the surface starts oscillating with time.", "fibs": ["point"]}
{"text": "At any instant, a photograph of the surface would show circular rings on which the disturbance is maximum.", "fibs": ["instant"]}
{"text": "Clearly, all points on such a circle are oscillating in phase because they are at the same distance from the source.", "fibs": ["circle"]}
{"text": "Such a locus of points, which oscillate in phase is called a wavefront; thus a wavefront is defined as a surface of constant phase.", "fibs": ["locus"]}
{"text": "The speed with which the wavefront moves outwards from the source is called the speed of the wave.", "fibs": ["speed"]}
{"text": "The energy of the wave travels in a direction perpendicular to the wavefront.", "fibs": ["energy"]}
{"text": "Figure 10.1 (a) A diverging spherical wave emanating from a point source.", "fibs": ["Figure"]}
{"text": "If we have a point source emitting waves uniformly in all directions, then the locus of points which have the same amplitude and vibrate in the same phase are spheres and we have what is known as a spherical wave as shown in Fig.", "fibs": ["point"]}
{"text": "10.1(a).", "fibs": ["10.1(a"]}
{"text": "At a large distance from the source, a small portion of the sphere can be considered as a plane and we have what is known as a plane wave [Fig.", "fibs": ["distance"]}
{"text": "10.1(b)].", "fibs": ["10.1(b"]}
{"text": "Figure 10.1 (b) At a large distance from the source, a small portion of the spherical wave can be approximated by a plane wave.", "fibs": ["Figure"]}
{"text": "Now, if we know the shape of the wavefront at t = 0, then Huygens principle allows us to determine the shape of the wavefront at a later time τ.", "fibs": ["shape"]}
{"text": "Thus, Huygens principle is essentially a geometrical construction, which given the shape of the wafefront at any time allows us to determine the shape of the wavefront at a later time.", "fibs": ["principle"]}
{"text": "Let us consider a diverging wave and let F1F2 represent a portion of the spherical wavefront at t = 0 (Fig.", "fibs": ["wave"]}
{"text": "Now, according to Huygens principle, each point of the wavefront is the source of a secondary disturbance and the wavelets emanating from these points spread out in all directions with the speed of the wave.", "fibs": ["principle"]}
{"text": "These wavelets emanating from the wavefront are usually referred to as secondary wavelets and if we draw a common tangent to all these spheres, we obtain the new position of the wavefront at a later time.", "fibs": ["wavefront"]}
{"text": "Thus, if we wish to determine the shape of the wavefront at t = τ, we draw spheres of radius vτ from each point on the spherical wavefront where v represents the speed of the waves in the medium.", "fibs": ["shape"]}
{"text": "If we now draw a common tangent to all these spheres, we obtain the new position of the wavefront at t = τ.", "fibs": ["position"]}
{"text": "The new wavefront shown as G1G2 in Fig.", "fibs": ["wavefront"]}
{"text": "10.2 is again spherical with point O as the centre.", "fibs": ["point"]}
{"text": "Figure 10.2 F1F2 represents the spherical wavefront (with O as centre) at t = 0.", "fibs": ["Figure"]}
{"text": "The envelope of the secondary wavelets emanating from F1F2 produces the forward moving wavefront G1G2.", "fibs": ["envelope"]}
{"text": "The backwave D1D2 does not exist.", "fibs": ["backwave"]}
{"text": "Figure 10.3 Huygens geometrical construction for a plane wave propagating to the right.", "fibs": ["Figure"]}
{"text": "F1 F2 is the plane wavefront at t = 0 and G1G2 is the wavefront at a later time τ.", "fibs": ["plane"]}
{"text": "The lines A1A2, B1B2 … etc., are normal to both F1F2 and G1G2 and represent rays.", "fibs": ["…"]}
{"text": "The above model has one shortcoming: we also have a backwave which is shown as D1D2 in Fig.", "fibs": ["model"]}
{"text": "Huygens argued that the amplitude of the secondary wavelets is maximum in the forward direction and zero in the backward direction; by making this adhoc assumption, Huygens could explain the absence of the backwave.", "fibs": ["amplitude"]}
{"text": "However, this adhoc assumption is not satisfactory and the absence of the backwave is really justified from more rigorous wave theory.", "fibs": ["adhoc"]}
{"text": "In a similar manner, we can use Huygens principle to determine the shape of the wavefront for a plane wave propagating through a medium (Fig.", "fibs": ["manner"]}
