{"text": "10.3.4  The doppler effect



We should mention here that one should be careful in constructing the wavefronts if the source (or the observer) is moving.", "fibs": ["doppler"]}
{"text": "For example, if there is no medium and the source moves away from the observer, then later wavefronts have to travel a greater distance to reach the observer and hence take a longer time.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "The time taken between the arrival of two successive wavefronts is hence longer at the observer than it is at the source.", "fibs": ["time"]}
{"text": "Thus, when the source moves away from the observer the frequency as measured by the source will be smaller.", "fibs": ["source"]}
{"text": "This is known as the Doppler effect.", "fibs": ["effect"]}
{"text": "Astronomers call the increase in wavelength due to doppler effect as  red shift since a wavelength in the middle of the visible region of the spectrum moves towards the red end of the spectrum.", "fibs": ["increase"]}
{"text": "When waves are received from a source moving towards the observer, there is an apparent decrease in wavelength, this is referred to as blue shift.", "fibs": ["source"]}
{"text": "You have already encountered Doppler effect for sound waves in Chapter 15 of Class XI textbook.", "fibs": ["effect"]}
{"text": "For velocities small compared to the speed of light, we can use the same formulae which we use for sound waves.", "fibs": ["speed"]}
