{"text": "10.5	Interference of Light Waves and Young’s Experiment
We will now discuss interference using light waves.", "fibs": ["’"]}
{"text": "If we use two sodium lamps illuminating two pinholes (Fig.", "fibs": ["use"]}
{"text": "10.11) we will not observe any interference fringes.", "fibs": ["interference"]}
{"text": "This is because of the fact that the light wave emitted from an ordinary source (like a sodium lamp) undergoes abrupt phase changes in times of the order of 10–10 seconds.", "fibs": ["fact"]}
{"text": "Thus the light waves coming out from two independent sources of light will not have any fixed phase relationship and would be incoherent, when this happens, as discussed in the previous section, the intensities on the screen will add up.", "fibs": ["light"]}
{"text": "The British physicist Thomas Young used an ingenious technique to “lock” the phases of the waves emanating from S1 and S2.", "fibs": ["physicist"]}
{"text": "He made two pinholes S1 and S2 (very close to each other) on an opaque screen [Fig.", "fibs": ["screen"]}
{"text": "10.12(a)].", "fibs": ["10.12(a"]}
{"text": "These were illuminated by another pinholes that was in turn, lit by a bright source.", "fibs": ["source"]}
{"text": "Light waves spread out from S and fall on both S1 and S2.", "fibs": ["spread"]}
{"text": "S1 and S2 then behave like two coherent sources because light waves coming out from S1 and S2 are derived from the same original source and any abrupt phase change in S will manifest in exactly similar phase changes in the light coming out from S1 and S2.", "fibs": ["light"]}
{"text": "Thus, the two sources S1 and S2 will be locked in phase; i.e., they will be coherent like the two vibrating needle in our water wave example [Fig.", "fibs": ["phase"]}
{"text": "10.8(a)].", "fibs": ["10.8(a"]}
