{"text": "We now have to sum up equal, coherent contributions from a large number of sources, each with a different phase.", "fibs": ["sum"]}
{"text": "This calculation was made by Fresnel using integral calculus, so we omit it here.", "fibs": ["calculation"]}
{"text": "The main features of the diffraction pattern can be understood by simple arguments.", "fibs": ["diffraction"]}
{"text": "At the central point C on the screen, the angle θ is zero.", "fibs": ["point"]}
{"text": "All path differences are zero and hence all the parts of the slit contribute in phase.", "fibs": ["path"]}
{"text": "This gives maximum intensity at C. Experimental observation shown in Fig.", "fibs": ["intensity"]}
{"text": "10.15 indicates that the intensity has a central maximum at θ = 0 and other secondary maxima at θ ≈  (n+1/2) λ/a, and has minima (zero intensity) at θ ≈  nλ/a, n = ±1, ±2, ±3, ....", "fibs": ["intensity"]}
{"text": "It is easy to see why it has minima at these values of angle.", "fibs": ["minima"]}
