Now, divide the slit into two equal halves LM and MN each of size a/2.", "fibs": ["slit"]}
{"text": "For every point M1 in LM, there is a point M2 in MN such that M1M2 = a/2.", "fibs": ["point"]}
{"text": "The path difference between M1 and M2 at P = M2P – M1P = θa/2 = λ/2 for the angle chosen.", "fibs": ["path"]}
{"text": "This means that the contributions from M1 and M2 are 180° out of phase and cancel in the direction θ = λ/a.", "fibs": ["180°"]}
{"text": "Contributions from the two halves of the slit LM and MN, therefore, cancel each other.", "fibs": ["slit"]}
{"text": "Equation (10.22) gives the angle at which the intensity falls to zero.", "fibs": ["Equation"]}
{"text": "One can similarly show that the intensity is zero for θ = nλ/a, with n being any integer (except zero!).", "fibs": ["show"]}
{"text": "Notice that the angular size of the central maximum increases when the slit width a decreases.", "fibs": ["Notice"]}
{"text": "Figure 10.15  The geometry of path differences for diffraction by a single slit.", "fibs": ["Figure"]}
{"text": "It is also easy to see why there are maxima at θ  = (n + 1/2) λ/a and why they go on becoming weaker and weaker with increasing n. Consider an angle θ = 3λ/2a which is midway between two of the dark fringes.", "fibs": ["maxima"]}
