{"text": "We now compare and contrast the interference pattern with that seen for a coherently illuminated single slit (usually called the single slit diffraction pattern).", "fibs": ["contrast"]}
{"text": "(i)	The interference pattern has a number of equally spaced  bright and dark bands.", "fibs": ["interference"]}
{"text": "The diffraction pattern has a central bright maximum  which is twice as wide as the other maxima.", "fibs": ["diffraction"]}
{"text": "The intensity falls as we go to successive maxima away from the centre, on either side.", "fibs": ["intensity"]}
{"text": "(ii)	We calculate the interference pattern by superposing two waves originating from the two narrow slits.", "fibs": ["ii"]}
{"text": "The diffraction pattern is a superposition of a continuous family of waves originating from each point on a single slit.", "fibs": ["diffraction"]}
{"text": "*	Richand Feynman was one of the recipients of the 1965 Nobel Prize in Physics for his fundamental work in quantum electrodynamics.", "fibs": ["work"]}
{"text": "(iii)	For a single slit of width a, the first null of the interference pattern occurs at  an angle of λ/a.", "fibs": ["iii"]}
{"text": "At the same angle of λ/a, we get a maximum (not a null) for two narrow slits separated by a distance a.", "fibs": ["angle"]}
{"text": "One must understand that both d and a have to be quite small, to be able to observe good interference and diffraction patterns.", "fibs": ["interference"]}
{"text": "For example, the separation d between the two slits must be of the order of a milimetre or so.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "The width a of each slit must be even smaller, of the order of 0.1 or 0.2 mm.", "fibs": ["width"]}
{"text": "In our discussion of Young’s experiment and the single-slit diffraction, we have assumed that the screen on which the fringes are formed is at a large distance.", "fibs": ["discussion"]}
{"text": "The two or more paths from the slits to the screen were treated as parallel.", "fibs": ["screen"]}
{"text": "This situation also occurs when we place a converging lens after the slits and place the screen at the focus.", "fibs": ["situation"]}
{"text": "Parallel paths from the slit are combined at a single point on the screen.", "fibs": ["slit"]}
{"text": "Note that the lens does not introduce any extra path differences in a parallel beam.", "fibs": ["lens"]}
{"text": "This arrangement is often used since it gives more intensity than placing the screen far away.", "fibs": ["arrangement"]}
{"text": "If f is the focal length of the lens, then we can easily work out  the size of the central bright maximum.", "fibs": ["f"]}
{"text": "In terms of angles, the separation of the central maximum from the first null of the diffraction pattern is λ/a.", "fibs": ["separation"]}
{"text": "Hence, the size on the screen will be f λ/a.", "fibs": ["size"]}
{"text": "10.6.2  Seeing the single slit diffraction pattern
It is surprisingly easy to see the single-slit diffraction pattern for oneself.", "fibs": ["slit"]}
{"text": "The equipment needed can be found in most homes –– two razor blades and one clear glass electric bulb preferably with a straight filament.", "fibs": ["equipment"]}
{"text": "One has to hold the two blades so that the edges are parallel and have a narrow slit in between.", "fibs": ["slit"]}
{"text": "This is easily done with the thumb and forefingers (Fig.", "fibs": ["thumb"]}
{"text": "10.18).", "fibs": ["10.18)"]}
{"text": "Keep the slit parallel to the filament, right in front of the eye.", "fibs": ["slit"]}
{"text": "With slight adjustment of the width of the slit and the parallelism of the edges, the pattern should be seen with its bright and dark bands.", "fibs": ["adjustment"]}
{"text": "Since the position of all the bands (except the central one) depends on wavelength, they will show some colours.", "fibs": ["position"]}
{"text": "Using a filter for red or blue will make the fringes clearer.", "fibs": ["filter"]}
{"text": "In this experiment, the filament plays the role of the first slit S in Fig.", "fibs": ["experiment"]}
{"text": "The lens of the eye focuses the pattern on the screen (the retina of the eye).", "fibs": ["lens"]}
{"text": "Figure 10.18 Holding two blades to form a single slit.", "fibs": ["Figure"]}
{"text": "A bulb filament viewed through this shows clear diffraction bands.", "fibs": ["bulb"]}
{"text": "With some effort, one can cut a double slit in an aluminium foil with a blade.", "fibs": ["effort"]}
{"text": "The bulb filament can be viewed as before to repeat Young’s experiment.", "fibs": ["bulb"]}
{"text": "In daytime, there is another suitable bright source subtending a small angle at the eye.", "fibs": ["source"]}
{"text": "This is the reflection of the Sun in any shiny convex surface (e.g., a cycle bell).", "fibs": ["reflection"]}
{"text": "Do not try direct sunlight – it can damage the eye and will not give fringes anyway as the Sun subtends an angle of (1/2)°.", "fibs": ["sunlight"]}
{"text": "In interference and diffraction, light energy is redistributed.", "fibs": ["interference"]}
{"text": "If it reduces in one region, producing a dark fringe, it increases in another region, producing a bright fringe.", "fibs": ["region"]}
{"text": "There is no gain or loss of energy, which is consistent with the principle of conservation of energy.", "fibs": ["gain"]}
{"text": "10.6.3  Resolving power of optical instruments
In Chapter 9 we had discussed about telescopes.", "fibs": ["power"]}
{"text": "The angular resolution of the telescope is determined by the objective of the telescope.", "fibs": ["resolution"]}
{"text": "The stars which are not resolved in the image produced by the objective cannot be resolved by any further magnification produced by the eyepiece.", "fibs": ["image"]}
{"text": "The primary purpose of the eyepiece is to provide magnification of the image produced by the objective.", "fibs": ["purpose"]}
{"text": "Consider a parallel beam of light falling on a convex lens.", "fibs": ["beam"]}
{"text": "If the lens is well corrected for aberrations, then geometrical optics tells us that the beam will get focused to a point.", "fibs": ["lens"]}
{"text": "However, because of diffraction, the beam instead of getting focused to a point gets focused to a spot of finite area.", "fibs": ["diffraction"]}
{"text": "In this case the effects due to diffraction can be taken into account by considering a plane wave incident on a circular aperture followed by a convex lens (Fig.", "fibs": ["case"]}
{"text": "The analysis of the corresponding diffraction pattern is quite involved; however, in principle, it is similar to the analysis carried out to obtain the single-slit diffraction pattern.", "fibs": ["analysis"]}
