{"text": "Determine the resolving power of your eye
You can estimate the resolving power of your eye with a simple experiment.", "fibs": ["power"]}
{"text": "Make black stripes of equal width separated by white stripes; see figure here.", "fibs": ["width"]}
{"text": "All the black stripes should be of equal width, while the width of the intermediate white stripes should increase as you go from the left to the right.", "fibs": ["width"]}
{"text": "For example, let all black stripes have a width of 5 mm.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "Let the width of the first two white stripes be 0.5 mm each, the next two white stripes be 1 mm each, the next two 1.5 mm each, etc.", "fibs": ["width"]}
{"text": "Paste this pattern on a wall in a room or laboratory, at the height of your eye.", "fibs": ["Paste"]}
{"text": "Now watch the pattern, preferably with one eye.", "fibs": ["pattern"]}
{"text": "By moving away or closer to the wall, find the position where you can just see some two black stripes as separate stripes.", "fibs": ["wall"]}
{"text": "All the black stripes to the left of this stripe would merge into one another and would not be distinguishable.", "fibs": ["stripe"]}
{"text": "On the other hand, the black stripes to the right of this would be more and more clearly visible.", "fibs": ["hand"]}
{"text": "Note the width d of the white stripe which separates the two regions, and measure the distance D of the wall from your eye.", "fibs": ["width"]}
{"text": "Then d/D is the resolution of your eye.", "fibs": ["d/D"]}
{"text": "You have watched specks of dust floating in air in a sunbeam entering through your window.", "fibs": ["dust"]}
{"text": "Find the distance (of a speck) which you can clearly see and distinguish from a neighbouring speck.", "fibs": ["distance"]}
{"text": "Knowing the resolution of your eye and the distance of the speck, estimate the size of the speck of dust.", "fibs": ["resolution"]}
