Equation (10.31) shows that for distances much smaller than zF , the spreading due to diffraction is smaller compared to the size of the beam.", "fibs": ["quantity"]}
{"text": "It becomes comparable when the distance is approximately  zF.", "fibs": ["distance"]}
{"text": "For distances much greater than zF, the spreading due to diffraction dominates over that due to ray optics (i.e., the size a of the aperture).", "fibs": ["zF"]}
{"text": "Equation (10.31) also shows that ray optics is valid in the limit of wavelength tending to zero.", "fibs": ["Equation"]}
{"text": "Example 10.7 For what distance is ray optics a good approximation when the aperture is 3 mm wide and the wavelength is 500 nm?", "fibs": ["Example"]}
{"text": "Solution  
This example shows that even with a small aperture, diffraction spreading can be neglected for rays many metres in length.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "Thus, ray optics is valid in many common situations.", "fibs": ["ray"]}
{"text": "10.7  Polarisation
Consider holding a long string that is held horizontally, the other end of which is assumed to be fixed.", "fibs": ["string"]}
{"text": "If we move the end of the string up and down in a periodic manner, we will generate a wave propagating  in the +x direction (Fig.", "fibs": ["move"]}
{"text": "Such a wave could be described by the following equation 



Figure 10.21 (a) The curves represent the displacement of a string at  t = 0 and at t = ∆t, respectively when a sinusoidal wave is propagating  in the +x-direction.", "fibs": ["wave"]}
{"text": "(b) The curve represents the time variation  of the displacement at x = 0 when a sinusoidal wave is propagating  in the +x-direction.", "fibs": ["b"]}
{"text": "At x = ∆x, the time variation of the displacement will be slightly displaced to the right.", "fibs": ["x"]}
{"text": "y (x,t) = a sin (kx – ωt)        (10.32)
where a and ω (= 2πν) represent the amplitude and the angular frequency of the wave, respectively; further, 
                      (10.33)
represents the wavelength associated with the wave.", "fibs": ["x,t"]}
{"text": "We had discussed propagation of such waves in Chapter 15 of Class XI textbook.", "fibs": ["propagation"]}
{"text": "Since the displacement (which is along the y direction) is at right angles to the direction of propagation of the wave, we have what is known as a transverse wave.", "fibs": ["displacement"]}
{"text": "Also, since the displacement is in the y direction, it is often referred to as a y-polarised wave.", "fibs": ["displacement"]}
{"text": "Since each point on the string moves on a straight line, the wave is also referred to as a linearly polarised wave.", "fibs": ["point"]}
{"text": "Further, the string always remains confined to the x-y plane and therefore it is also referred to as a plane polarised wave.", "fibs": ["string"]}
{"text": "In a similar manner we can consider the vibration of the string in the x-z plane generating a z-polarised wave whose displacement will be given by



z (x,t) = a sin (kx – ωt)	(10.34)
It should be mentioned that the linearly polarised waves [described by Eqs.", "fibs": ["manner"]}
{"text": "(10.33) and (10.34)] are all transverse waves; i.e., the displacement of each point of the string is always at right angles to the direction of propagation of the wave.", "fibs": ["displacement"]}
{"text": "Finally, if the plane of vibration of the string is changed randomly in very short intervals of time, then we have what is known as an unpolarised wave.", "fibs": ["plane"]}
{"text": "Thus, for an unpolarised wave the displacement will be randomly changing with time though it will always be perpendicular to the direction of propagation.", "fibs": ["wave"]}
{"text": "Light waves are transverse in nature; i.e., the electric field associated with a propagating light wave is always at right angles to the direction of propagation of the wave.", "fibs": ["nature"]}
{"text": "This can be easily demonstrated using a simple polaroid.", "fibs": ["polaroid"]}
{"text": "You must have seen thin plastic like sheets, which are called polaroids.", "fibs": ["plastic"]}
{"text": "A polaroid consists of long chain molecules aligned in a particular direction.", "fibs": ["polaroid"]}
{"text": "The electric vectors (associated with the propagating light wave) along the direction of the aligned molecules get absorbed.", "fibs": ["light"]}
{"text": "Thus, if an unpolarised light wave is incident on such a polaroid then the light wave will get linearly polarised with the electric vector oscillating along a direction perpendicular to the aligned molecules; this direction is known as the pass-axis of the polaroid.", "fibs": ["light"]}
{"text": "Thus, if the light from an ordinary source (like a sodium lamp) passes through a polaroid sheet P1, it is observed that its intensity is reduced by half.", "fibs": ["light"]}
{"text": "Rotating P1 has no effect on the transmitted beam and transmitted intensity remains constant.", "fibs": ["effect"]}
{"text": "Now, let an identical piece of polaroid P2 be placed before P1.", "fibs": ["piece"]}
{"text": "As expected, the light from the lamp is reduced in intensity on passing through P2 alone.", "fibs": ["light"]}
{"text": "But now rotating P1 has a dramatic effect on the light coming from P2.", "fibs": ["effect"]}
{"text": "In one position, the intensity transmitted by P2 followed by P1 is nearly zero.", "fibs": ["position"]}
{"text": "When turned by 90° from this position, P1 transmits nearly the full intensity emerging from P2 (Fig.", "fibs": ["90°"]}
{"text": "The above experiment can be easily understood by assuming that light passing through the polaroid P2 gets polarised along  the pass-axis of  P2.", "fibs": ["experiment"]}
{"text": "If the pass-axis of  P2 makes an angle θ with the pass-axis of  P1, then  when the polarised beam passes through the polaroid P2, the component  E cos θ  (along the pass-axis of P2) will pass through P2.", "fibs": ["angle"]}
{"text": "Thus, as we rotate the polaroid P1 (or P2), the intensity will vary as:
I = I0 cos2θ	(10.35)
where I0 is the intensity of the polarized light after passing through P1.", "fibs": ["polaroid"]}
{"text": "This is known as Malus’ law.", "fibs": ["’"]}
{"text": "The above discussion shows that the intensity coming out of a single polaroid is half of the incident intensity.", "fibs": ["discussion"]}
{"text": "By putting a second polaroid, the intensity can be further controlled from 50% to zero of the incident intensity by adjusting the angle between the pass-axes of two polaroids.", "fibs": ["polaroid"]}
{"text": "Figure 10.22 (a) Passage of light through two polaroids P2 and P1.", "fibs": ["Figure"]}
{"text": "The transmitted fraction falls from 1 to 0 as the angle between them varies from 0° to 90°.", "fibs": ["fraction"]}
{"text": "Notice that the light seen through a single polaroid  P1 does not vary with angle.", "fibs": ["Notice"]}
{"text": "(b) Behaviour of the electric vector when light passes through two polaroids.", "fibs": ["b"]}
{"text": "The transmitted polarisation is the component parallel to the polaroid axis.The double arrows show the oscillations of the electric vector.", "fibs": ["polarisation"]}
{"text": "Polaroids can be used to control the intensity, in sunglasses, windowpanes, etc.", "fibs": ["control"]}
{"text": "Polaroids are also used in photographic cameras and 3D movie cameras.", "fibs": ["movie"]}
