{"text": "10.7.1  Polarisation by scattering 
The light from a clear blue portion of the sky shows a rise and fall of intensity when viewed through a polaroid which is rotated.", "fibs": ["light"]}
{"text": "This is nothing but sunlight, which has changed its direction (having been scattered) on encountering the molecules of the earth’s atmosphere.", "fibs": ["nothing"]}
{"text": "As Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "10.23(a) shows, the incident sunlight is unpolarised.", "fibs": ["10.23(a"]}
{"text": "The dots stand for polarisation perpendicular to the plane of the figure.", "fibs": ["polarisation"]}
{"text": "The double arrows show polarisation in the plane of the figure.", "fibs": ["show"]}
{"text": "(There is no phase relation between these two in unpolarised light).", "fibs": ["phase"]}
{"text": "Under the influence of the electric field of the incident wave the electrons in the molecules acquire components of motion in both these directions.", "fibs": ["influence"]}
{"text": "We have drawn an observer looking at 90° to the direction of the sun.", "fibs": ["observer"]}
{"text": "Clearly, charges accelerating parallel to the double arrows do not radiate energy towards this observer since their acceleration has no transverse component.", "fibs": ["energy"]}
{"text": "The radiation scattered by the molecule is therefore represented by dots.", "fibs": ["radiation"]}
{"text": "It is polarised perpendicular to the plane of the figure.", "fibs": ["plane"]}
{"text": "This explains the polarisation of scattered light from the sky.", "fibs": ["polarisation"]}
{"text": "FIGURE 10.23 (a) Polarisation of the blue scattered light from the sky.", "fibs": ["FIGURE"]}
{"text": "The incident sunlight is unpolarised (dots and arrows).", "fibs": ["incident"]}
{"text": "A typical molecule is shown.", "fibs": ["molecule"]}
{"text": "It scatters light by 90° polarised normal to the plane of the paper (dots only).", "fibs": ["light"]}
{"text": "(b) Polarisation of light reflected from a transparent medium at the Brewster angle (reflected ray perpendicular to refracted ray).", "fibs": ["b"]}
{"text": "The scattering of light by molecules was intensively investigated by C.V. Raman and his collaborators in Kolkata in the 1920s.", "fibs": ["light"]}
{"text": "Raman was awarded the Nobel Prize for Physics in 1930 for this work.", "fibs": ["work"]}
{"text": "A SPECIAL CASE OF TOTAL TRANSMISSION
When light is incident on an interface of two media, it is observed that some part of it gets reflected and some part gets transmitted.", "fibs": ["SPECIAL"]}
{"text": "Consider a related question: Is it possible that under some conditions a monochromatic beam of light incident on a surface (which is normally reflective) gets completely transmitted with no reflection?", "fibs": ["question"]}
{"text": "To your surprise, the answer is yes.Let us try a simple experiment and check what happens.", "fibs": ["surprise"]}
{"text": "Arrange a laser, a good polariser, a prism and screen as shown in the figure here.Let the light emitted by the laser source pass through the polariser and be incident on the surface of the prism at the Brewster’s angle of incidence iB.", "fibs": ["laser"]}
{"text": "Now rotate the polariser carefully and you will observe that for a specific alignment of the polariser, the light incident on the prism is completely transmitted and no light is reflected from the surface of the prism.", "fibs": ["polariser"]}
{"text": "The reflected spot will completely vanish.", "fibs": ["spot"]}
{"text": "10.7.2  Polarisation by reflection
Figure 10.23(b) shows light reflected from a transparent medium, say, water.", "fibs": ["reflection"]}
{"text": "As before, the dots and arrows indicate that both polarisations are present in the incident and refracted waves.", "fibs": ["incident"]}
{"text": "We have drawn a situation in which the reflected wave travels at right angles to the refracted wave.", "fibs": ["situation"]}
{"text": "The oscillating electrons in the water produce the reflected wave.", "fibs": ["water"]}
{"text": "These move in the two directions transverse to the radiation from wave in the medium, i.e., the refracted wave.", "fibs": ["move"]}
{"text": "The arrows are parallel to the direction of the reflected wave.", "fibs": ["direction"]}
{"text": "Motion in this direction does not contribute to the reflected wave.", "fibs": ["direction"]}
{"text": "As the figure shows, the reflected light is therefore linearly polarised perpendicular to the plane of the figure (represented by dots).", "fibs": ["figure"]}
{"text": "This can be checked by looking at the reflected light through an analyser.", "fibs": ["light"]}
{"text": "The transmitted intensity will be zero when the axis of the analyser is in the plane of the figure, i.e., the plane of incidence.", "fibs": ["intensity"]}
{"text": "When unpolarised light is incident on the boundary between two transparent media, the reflected light is polarised with its electric vector perpendicular to the plane of incidence when the  refracted and reflected rays make a right angle with each other.", "fibs": ["light"]}
{"text": "Thus we have seen that when reflected wave is perpendicular to the refracted wave, the reflected wave is a totally polarised wave.", "fibs": ["wave"]}
{"text": "The angle of incidence in this case is called Brewster’s angle and is denoted by iB.", "fibs": ["angle"]}
{"text": "We can see that iB is related to the refractive index of the denser medium.", "fibs": ["iB"]}
{"text": "Since we have iB+r = π/2, we get from Snell’s law

	(10.36)
This is known as Brewster’s law.", "fibs": ["iB+r"]}
{"text": "Example 10.9 Unpolarised light is incident on a plane glass surface.", "fibs": ["Example"]}
{"text": "What should be the angle of incidence so that the reflected and refracted rays are perpendicular to each other?", "fibs": ["angle"]}
{"text": "Solution For i + r to be equal to π/2, we should have tan iB = µ = 1.5.", "fibs": ["r"]}
{"text": "This gives iB = 57°.", "fibs": ["iB"]}
{"text": "This is the Brewster’s angle for air to glass interface.", "fibs": ["’"]}
{"text": "For simplicity, we have discussed scattering of light by 90°, and reflection at the Brewster angle.", "fibs": ["simplicity"]}
{"text": "In this special situation, one of the two perpendicular components of the electric field is zero.", "fibs": ["situation"]}
{"text": "There is no stable phase relationship between the two perpendicular components since these are derived from two perpendicular components of an unpolarised beam.", "fibs": ["phase"]}
{"text": "When such light is viewed through a rotating analyser, one sees a maximum and a minimum of intensity but not complete darkness.", "fibs": ["light"]}
{"text": "This kind of light is called partially polarised.", "fibs": ["kind"]}
{"text": "Let us try to understand the situation.", "fibs": ["situation"]}
{"text": "When an unpolarised beam of light is incident at the Brewster’s angle on an interface of two media, only part of light with electric field vector perpendicular to the plane of incidence will be reflected.", "fibs": ["beam"]}
{"text": "Now by using a good polariser, if we completely remove all the light with its electric vector perpendicular to the plane of incidence and let this light be incident on the surface of the prism at Brewster’s angle, you will then observe no reflection and there will be total transmission of light.", "fibs": ["polariser"]}
{"text": "We began this chapter by pointing out that there are some phenomena which can be explained only by the wave theory.", "fibs": ["chapter"]}
{"text": "In order to develop a proper understanding, we first described how some phenomena like reflection and refraction, which were studied on this basis of Ray Optics in Chapter 9, can also be understood on the basis of Wave Optics.", "fibs": ["order"]}
{"text": "Then we described Young’s double slit experiment which was a turning point in the study of optics.", "fibs": ["’"]}
{"text": "Finally, we described some associated points such as diffraction, resolution, polarisation, and validity of ray optics.", "fibs": ["diffraction"]}
{"text": "In the next chapter, you will see how new experiments led to new theories at the turn of the century around 1900 A.D.


Summary
1.", "fibs": ["chapter"]}
{"text": "Huygens’ principle tells us that each point on a wavefront is a source of secondary waves, which add up to give the wavefront at a later time.", "fibs": ["’"]}
{"text": "Huygens’ construction tells us that the new wavefront is the forward envelope of the secondary waves.", "fibs": ["’"]}
{"text": "When the speed of light is independent of direction, the secondary waves are spherical.", "fibs": ["speed"]}
{"text": "The rays are then perpendicular to both the wavefronts and the time of travel is the same measured along any ray.", "fibs": ["time"]}
{"text": "This principle leads to the well known laws of reflection and refraction.", "fibs": ["principle"]}
{"text": "The principle of superposition of waves applies whenever two or more sources of light illuminate the same point.", "fibs": ["principle"]}
{"text": "When we consider the intensity of light due to these sources at the given point, there is an interference term in addition to the sum of the individual intensities.", "fibs": ["intensity"]}
{"text": "But this term is important only if it has a non-zero average, which occurs only if the sources have the same frequency and a stable phase difference.", "fibs": ["term"]}
{"text": "Young’s double slit of separation d gives equally spaced fringes of angular separation λ/d.", "fibs": ["’"]}
{"text": "The source, mid-point of the slits, and central bright fringe lie in a straight line.", "fibs": ["source"]}
{"text": "An extended source will destroy the fringes if it subtends angle more than λ/d at the slits.", "fibs": ["source"]}
{"text": "A single slit of width a gives a diffraction pattern with a central maximum.", "fibs": ["slit"]}
{"text": "The intensity falls to zero at angles of  etc., with successively weaker secondary maxima in between.", "fibs": ["intensity"]}
{"text": "Diffraction limits the angular resolution of a telescope to λ/D where D is the diameter.", "fibs": ["Diffraction"]}
{"text": "Similarly, a microscope objective subtending angle 2β at the focus, in a medium of refractive index n, will just separate two objects spaced at a distance λ/(2n sin β), which is the resolution limit of a microscope.", "fibs": ["microscope"]}
{"text": "Diffraction determines the limitations of the concept of light rays.", "fibs": ["Diffraction"]}
{"text": "A beam of width atravels a distance a2/λ, called the Fresnel distance, before it starts to spread out due to diffraction.", "fibs": ["beam"]}
{"text": "Natural light, e.g., from the sun is unpolarised.", "fibs": ["light"]}
{"text": "This means the electric vector takes all possible directions in the transverse plane, rapidly and randomly, during a measurement.", "fibs": ["vector"]}
{"text": "A polaroid transmits only one component (parallel to a special axis).", "fibs": ["polaroid"]}
{"text": "The resulting light is called linearly polarised or plane polarised.", "fibs": ["light"]}
{"text": "When this kind of light is viewed through a second polaroid whose axis turns through 2π, two maxima and minima of intensity are seen.", "fibs": ["kind"]}
{"text": "Polarised light can also be produced by reflection at a special angle (called the Brewster angle) and by scattering through π/2 in the earth’s atmosphere.", "fibs": ["light"]}
{"text": "Waves from a point source spread out in all directions, while light was seen to travel along  narrow  rays.", "fibs": ["point"]}
{"text": "It required the insight and experiment of Huygens, Young and Fresnel to understand how a wave theory could explain all aspects of the behaviour of light.", "fibs": ["insight"]}
{"text": "The crucial new feature of waves is interference of amplitudes from different sources which can be both constructive and destructive, as shown in Young’s experiment.", "fibs": ["feature"]}
{"text": "Diffraction phenomena define the limits of ray optics.", "fibs": ["Diffraction"]}
{"text": "The limit of the ability of microscopes and telescopes to distinguish very close objects is set by the wavelength of light.", "fibs": ["limit"]}
{"text": "Most interference and diffraction effects exist even for longitudinal waves like sound in air.", "fibs": ["interference"]}
{"text": "But polarisation phenomena are special to transverse waves like light waves.", "fibs": ["polarisation"]}
